{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.13,0.48,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77039"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11444"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10589"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26507"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77039"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, prolactin levels rise steadily but milk production does not begin until after delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains why lactation is inhibited during pregnancy despite high prolactin levels?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low oxytocin levels","Inadequate prolactin receptor expression","High oestrogen levels block prolactin effects","Progesterone deficiency","Insufficient mammary gland development"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh oestrogen levels block prolactin effects\u003C/strong\u003E on mammary tissue, preventing milk production despite elevated prolactin. After delivery, oestrogen levels fall dramatically, removing this inhibition and allowing prolactin to stimulate lactation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsufficient mammary gland development\u003C/strong\u003E - Mammary tissue is fully developed by late pregnancy due to the effects of oestrogen, progesterone and other hormones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow oxytocin levels\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxytocin is responsible for milk ejection (let-down) rather than milk production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E - Progesterone levels are high during pregnancy and contribute to mammary development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInadequate prolactin receptor expression\u003C/strong\u003E - Prolactin receptors are present throughout pregnancy but their signalling is blocked by oestrogen\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initiation of lactation after delivery is therefore primarily due to the removal of oestrogen\u0027s inhibitory effects, allowing prolactin to stimulate milk production in the prepared mammary tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prolactin stimulates milk production in mammary glands but its effects are blocked by high oestrogen levels during pregnancy.","After delivery, falling oestrogen levels allow prolactin to initiate lactation.","Suckling stimulates continued prolactin release through neural pathways to maintain milk production."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:53:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:53:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11444"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77039"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type